The paper discusses the use of generative adversarial networks (GANs) in solving density estimation problems, which is a common topic in the machine learning subfield of "deep learning" (cs.LG). The paper specifically focuses on the use of Wasserstein GANs, which is a popular approach in the field of neural engineering (cs.NE). The paper also discusses the use of function decompositions, which is a common technique in computer vision (cs.CV) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper discusses the potential for scaling these techniques to higher dimensional problems, which is a common topic in the subfield of signal processing (cs.SI).
